
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `efibootdump` baraye didan va gereftan etela'at az `EFIVARS` (variables EFI) estefade mishavad. In dastoor behetoon komak mikone ke darke behtari az boot options-e systemetoon dashte bashid. Basically, etela'ate boot ra mikhune va neshoon mide.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `efibootdump` --> Namayesh hameye etela'ate default boot.
    🔹 `efibootdump -v` --> 💬 Namayesh etela'ate bishtar (verbose mode).
    🔹 `efibootdump -t` --> ⏱️ Namayesh timezone.
    🔹 `efibootdump -h` --> ℹ️ Namayesh rahnama (help).

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ efibootdump

    🔹 Namayesh etela'ate boot default.

    $ efibootdump -v

    🔹 Namayesh etela'ate boot ba details bishtar.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ efibootdump | grep "BootOrder"

    🔹 Peida kardan BootOrder az output efibootdump. Shoma mitoneen dastoor `grep` ra ba gozine-ha va kalame-haye digar estefade konin ta natijeye morde nazar ro peida konin.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `efibootdump` command is used to view and retrieve information from `EFIVARS` (EFI variables). This command helps you gain a better understanding of your system's boot options. Basically, it reads and displays boot information.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `efibootdump` --> Display all default boot information.
    🔹 `efibootdump -v` --> 💬 Display more detailed information (verbose mode).
    🔹 `efibootdump -t` --> ⏱️ Display timezone information.
    🔹 `efibootdump -h` --> ℹ️ Display help information.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ efibootdump

    🔹 Display default boot information.

    $ efibootdump -v

    🔹 Display boot information with more details.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ efibootdump | grep "BootOrder"

    🔹 Find the BootOrder from the efibootdump output. You can use the `grep` command with other options and keywords to find specific results.
